<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/promise-from-european-central-bank-is-also-a-gamble/" data-title="Promise From European Central Bank Is Also a Gamble" data-description="The European Central Bank plans to buy bonds backed by loans to consumers and companies starting next month.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By promising to rev up the printing presses, the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_central_bank/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about European Central Bank">European Central Bank</a> has created hope in the markets that Europe may finally start to overcome its economic challenges.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet the central bank is taking a big gamble in directing much of the stimulus at a complex securities market that for several years has been struggling to get back on its feet.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/d/mario_draghi/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Mario Draghi.">Mario Draghi</a>, the president of the European Central Bank, said on Thursday that the bank would soon start to buy bonds that are backed by loans made to consumers and companies. He did not say how much the central bank would be willing to spend on these loan-backed bonds. But the purchases could make up a substantial share of the roughly 1 trillion euros, or $1.3 trillion, that Mr. Draghi implied that the bank was prepared to spend.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThis is meaningful,â said Antonio Garcia Pascual, chief economist for the euro area at <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BCS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Barclays PLC">Barclays</a>. âHe is definitely delivering.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many things have to come together for the plan to buy loan-backed bonds to work.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bond-buying plan homes in on one of the biggest threats to Europeâs economy: a decline in bank lending. Loans to corporations have declined by $740 billion since the 2008 financial crisis, according to the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/royal-bank-of-scotland-group-plc/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Royal Bank of Scotland.">Royal Bank of Scotland</a>. Notably, a large proportion of that slump occurred in the last two years, a period when bank lending to corporations has been growing strongly in the United States.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Europeâs bond-buying program could help open the credit spigot by freeing up lending capacity at its banks. In essence, the program would try to get a vast lending pipeline that had fueled developed economies before the 2008 crisis flowing powerfully again. In a process called securitization, banks make loans and then package them into bonds, which are then sold to investors like mutual funds, pensions and hedge funds. This pipeline can funnel money from a wide array of creditors to individuals and corporate borrowers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One of its biggest advantages is that the banks that actually make the loans can quickly sell them, freeing up financial resources to make even more loans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But investors lost confidence in the securitization market in 2008, when it became clear that banks had abused the market by using the process to offload shoddy mortgages. Securitization has returned in earnest for certain types of loans in the United States, but in Europe it remains well below precrisis levels. As a result, the Continent is even more reliant on its banks, many of which are struggling with bad loans and face regulatory stress tests this fall that aim to gauge if they have enough capital.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nonetheless, this is how the bond-buying plan, in theory, could turn things around.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Banks would sell large amounts of loan-backed bonds to the European Central Bank, or into a revived bond market, gaining cash that they could then use to make new loans. And even if the banks donât do large amounts of new lending, selling old loans at good prices could help banks meet any new capital targets that may emerge from the stress tests.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Central bank bond buying can also stimulate the system in other ways. It lowers interest rates across the system, and it brings new investors into the credit markets, increasing the amount of money available for lending.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hedge funds, for instance, have been buying loan-backed bonds in anticipation of the European stimulus.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThese initiatives announced by Draghi are an important step towards repairing Europeâs financial plumbing,â said Jason Walker, a portfolio manager at CQS Management, a British hedge fund. The firm, which has a $2 billion fund that invests in asset-backed securities, has been buying Spanish residential mortgage backed securities since the start of this year â and over the last week it has increased its buying, according to its latest note to investors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The central bankâs actions could be a particular boon for hedge funds and <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/private-equity/?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about private equity.">private equity</a> firms that have raised billions of dollars to scoop up distressed assets in Europe. They have had a hard time finding investments, because the banks holding many of these assets have been reluctant to sell at what they consider to be fire sale prices.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bond-buying plan could flop, however.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It might, for instance, end up being too small to make a difference to Europeâs economy. Mr. Draghi said the details of the program would be announced early in October and the buying would begin then.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Whatever the central bank decides about the size, it will be partly limited by the relative smallness of Europeâs markets for loan-backed bonds. For instance, there are about $2 trillion of bonds in Europe that are backed by loans, including mortgage-backed securities, according to data from the Securities Industry and Financial Markets Association, or Sifma.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The European Central Bank said it is also prepared to buy covered bonds, which are securities backed by cash flows from loans that remain on the bankâs books. There are around $2.7 trillion of covered bonds tied to mortgages. But the two pools of European bonds only add up to about half of the $10.2 trillion in loan-backed bonds in the United States.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And the bond buying may just create a flurry of market speculation that does little for the real economies of Europe and creates the impression that policy makers are making progress when deep divisions may still exist between European countries.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf asset prices do rise in unison, then my concern is that it is not warranted, given the political circumstances in Europe and the fact that the Continent is divided on E.C.B. policy,â said Mark Jurish of Larch Lane Advisors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">European banks may not have been lending for sensible reasons. The creditworthiness of European companies may be too low for the banksâ tastes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But even if buying loan-backed bonds falls short, Mr. Draghi has another option. The European Central Bank could also start buying government bonds, something that the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/f/federal_reserve_system/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Federal Reserve System.">Federal Reserve</a> did in what became known in the markets as <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/q/quantitative_easing/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about quantitative easing.">quantitative easing</a>, or Q.E.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf they have to do more it will have to be full-blown Q.E. that includes government bonds,â said Mr. Garcia Pascual of Barclays.</p>
